'''Joseph Frizell''' (13 March 1832 - 4 May 1910) was an American engineer. He is notable for having independently derived the fundamental equations to describe the velocity of a [[shock wave]] ([[Water hammer]] equations) in 1898<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Frizell|first=Joseph Palmer|date=1898|title=Pressures resulting from changes of velocity of water in pipes. Paper 819 presented 6 October 1897.|url=|journal=Transactions of the ASCE|volume=39|pages=1–18|via=}}</ref> and for his book Water-Power<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/waterpowerout00frizrich|title=Water-power, an outline of the development and application of the energy of flowing water|last=Frizell|first=Joseph Palmer|publisher=J. Wiley & sons|year=1901|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> in 1901, which was the first practical book on [[hydraulics]] in the USA.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/933441891|title=Hydraulicians in the USA 1800-2000 : A biographical dictionary of leaders in hydraulic engineering and fluid mechanics|last=Hager|first=Willi|date=|publisher=CRC Press|year=2015|isbn=9781315680125|location=|pages=2058|oclc=933441891}}</ref> I was a major milestone in the engienering knowledge, as Schutze wrote ″As an hydraulic engineer, Frizell was prominent, and his book, Waterpower, filled a definitive need in the technology of that day.″<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015078460238;view=1up;seq=5|title=Hydraulic Air Compressors|last=Schulze|first=Leroy E.|publisher=United States Department of Interior|date=May 1954|page=6}}</ref>

